AI Costs: When the Benjamin is Worth It
I am SO tired of paying for tools but in a world where we get 10-100x lever=
age=E2=80=A6it=E2=80=99s hard to say no because I see the value adding up s=
o quick.
I grimaced at the credit card bill when I saw the $100/month charge for my =
Claude subscription. As someone who already pays for ChatGPT and other AI t=
ools, adding another subscription felt excessive. But what happened next fu=
ndamentally changed how I think about the economics of AI tools.
It's 20x the value for 4-5x the money. This isn=E2=80=99t hyperbole=E2=80=
=94it feels like a conservative estimate after watching Claude Code build m=
y entire website while I chatted with a pal. Not a template. Not a rough dr=
aft. A complete, professional site with sophisticated animations and a desi=
gn system I'd actually use. I still need to plug in the content and polish,=
 but the site itself (at core) is more or less done.
I'd installed Claude Code thinking I'd get a souped-up coding assistant=E2=
=80=94something to go brrrrt and print lines of code in React from the term=
inal. The 5-minute setup was surprisingly charming, complete with what I ca=
lled a cute Claude graphic that felt like an 80's video game. The terminal =
interface should have intimidated me, but instead, it felt approachable, al=
most playful.
What I discovered was something entirely different from my expectations. Th=
is isn=E2=80=99t just Claude stuffed into a terminal. It feels different, m=
ore powerful. And I think that=E2=80=99s because it makes mistakes less.
Calling it a junior dev is probably technically accurate but undersells the=
 vibe. When I started asking strategic questions=E2=80=94"What's the right =
ordering of this project if I want particular capabilities to update afterw=
ard?"=E2=80=94Claude Code more or less steps up. It isn=E2=80=99t just impl=
ementing my ideas; it=E2=80=99s thinking through architectures, planning mu=
lti-step workflows, and making decisions I'd expect from a more senior engi=
neer, although I=E2=80=99m not ignoring the fact that it still has limited =
visibility, (somewhat) limited memory=E2=80=94stuff that a senior engineer =
isn=E2=80=99t plagued with (most days anyway lol).
The real shock? That this is happening in the terminal, turning what has fe=
lt like an archaic interface into a command center for a new way of buildin=
g software. This is the story of how a $100 monthly subscription became a m=
ust-have investment=E2=80=94and why you might be just 5 minutes away from t=
he same transformation.
What Claude Code Actually Is (And Isn't)
Let me clear up the biggest misconception right away: Claude Code is not ju=
